04554nam a22006615i 9780292744509DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212012txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927445097 a10.7560/7436182doi  a(DE-B1597)587415  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aHJ247b.H64 2012eb 7aBUS0230002bisacsh1 aHogeland, William, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFounding Finance :bHow Debt, Speculation, Foreclosures, Protests, and Crackdowns Made Us a Nation /cWilliam Hogeland. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2012  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1 The Founders, Finance, and Us (2012) -- t2 Riot, Regulate, Occupy (1765–1771) -- t3 Two Revolutions? (1771–1776) -- t4 Conceived in War Debt (1776–1783) -- t5 History on the Verge of a Nervous Breakdown (1913–2012) -- t6 An Existential Interpretation of the Constitution of the United States (1783–1789) -- t7 It’s Hamilton’s America . . . We Just Live in It (1789–1791) -- t8 Crackdown and Lockup Cincinnatus, the Whiskey Rebels, and the End of Thomas Paine (1791– ) -- t9 Gather Your Armies (2012) -- tAcknowledgments -- tBibliographic Essay -- tReferences -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRecent movements such as the Tea Party and anti-tax “constitutional conservatism” lay claim to the finance and taxation ideas of America’s founders, but how much do we really know about the dramatic clashes over finance and economics that marked the founding of America? Dissenting from both right-wing claims and certain liberal preconceptions, Founding Finance brings to life the violent conflicts over economics, class, and finance that played directly, and in many ways ironically, into the hardball politics of forming the nation and ratifying the Constitution—conflicts that still continue to affect our politics, legislation, and debate today. Mixing lively narrative with fresh views of America’s founders, William Hogeland offers a new perspective on America’s economic infancy: foreclosure crises that make our current one look mild; investment bubbles in land and securities that drove rich men to high-risk borrowing and mad displays of ostentation before dropping them into debtors’ prisons; depressions longer and deeper than the great one of the twentieth century; crony mercantilism, war profiteering, and government corruption that undermine any nostalgia for a virtuous early republic; and predatory lending of scarce cash at exorbitant, unregulated rates, which forced people into bankruptcy, landlessness, and working in the factories and on the commercial farms of their creditors. This story exposes and corrects a perpetual historical denial—by movements across the political spectrum—of America’s all-important founding economic clashes, a denial that weakens and cheapens public discourse on American finance just when we need it most.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aDebts, PubliczUnited StatesxHistoryy1789-1801. 0aFinance, PubliczUnited StatesxHistoryy1789-1801. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/74361840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292744509423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292744509/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK